  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css" />
</head>
<body>


  <nav id="navbar">
    <header>Python Documentation</header>
    <a class="nav-link" href="#Introduction">Introduction</a>
    <a class="nav-link" href="#Hello_World">Hello World</a>
    <a class="nav-link" href="#Variables_and_Data_Types">Variables and Data Types</a>
    <a class="nav-link" href="#Control_Flow">Control Flow</a>
    <a class="nav-link" href="#Functions">Functions</a>
  </nav>


  <main id="main-doc">


    <section class="main-section" id="Introduction">
      <header>Introduction</header>
      <p>Python is a high-level, interpreted, interactive and object-oriented scripting language. It is designed to be highly readable, frequently utilizing English keywords where other languages use punctuation.</p>
      <p>It is dynamically typed and garbage-collected, supporting multiple programming paradigms including procedural, object-oriented, and functional programming models. To start running code, you must have the <code>python3</code> interpreter installed on your workstation environment.</p>
    </section>


    <section class="main-section" id="Hello_World">
      <header>Hello World</header>
      <p>Getting started with programming in Python is remarkably simple. You do not need complex boilerplate wrappers, main class declarations, or structural namespaces to output text to your standard stream console.</p>
      <p>To run your initial application, simply invoke the built-in system output terminal routine like this:</p>
      <pre><code>print("Hello, World!")</code></pre>
      <p>Execute the source file directly using your shell command framework: <code>python app.py</code>.</p>
    </section>


    <section class="main-section" id="Variables_and_Data_Types">
      <header>Variables and Data Types</header>
      <p>In Python, variables do not require explicit declaration to reserve memory space. The declaration happens automatically when you assign a value to a variable using the <code>=</code> operator.</p>
      <p>Python handles data mapping implicitly through highly optimized primitive variants. Standard built-in data collections include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Numbers:</strong> Handles integers and floating-point data values.</li>
        <li><strong>Strings:</strong> Continuous sets of characters represented in quotation sets.</li>
        <li><strong>Lists:</strong> Ordered array sets initialized via <code>[item, item]</code> layout patterns.</li>
        <li><strong>Tuples:</strong> Immutable read-only sequences wrapped inside parentheses.</li>
        <li><strong>Dictionaries:</strong> Key-value hash tables configured using curly bracket layouts.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>For example, initializing a plain dynamic sequence or string sequence structure is as clean as writing: <code>user_age = 25</code>.</p>
    </section>


    <section class="main-section" id="Control_Flow">
      <header>Control Flow</header>
      <p>Python structural flow configurations rely exclusively on semantic clean text structures rather than wrapping statements inside curly brackets.</p>
      <p>Decision structural execution paths use standard keyword arguments like <code>if</code>, <code>elif</code>, and <code>else</code> blocks:</p>
      <pre><code>if user_age >= 18:
    print("Access Granted")
else:
    print("Access Denied")</code></pre>
      <p>Remember to always include the trailing colon syntax separator when configuring dynamic blocks.</p>
    </section>


    <section class="main-section" id="Functions">
      <header>Functions</header>
      <p>A function is a block of organized, reusable code that is used to perform a single, related action. Functions provide better modularity for your application and a high degree of code reusing.</p>
      <p>You can define functions to provide required functionality. Here is the simple syntax rule to create custom blocks:</p>
      <pre><code>def greet_user(name):
    return f"Welcome back, {name}!"</code></pre>
      <p>To execute the code logic, simply call your specified naming sequence directly from alternative code runtimes.</p>
    </section>


  </main>


</body>
</html>
